fields.precision_treatment: The patient’s case, including previous treatments, clinical course, and genomic analysis were presented at our institution’s molecular tumor board.  Participating in the tumor board were both intramural and extramural experts in the fields of medical oncology, cancer genomics, cancer cell biology, cells signaling and pharmacy.  The panel consensus was that a tumor with the indicated molecular aberrations would have an increased likelihood of responding to anti-Her2 targeted therapies including Trastuzumab or Trastuzumab-emtansine (TD-M1).  Extensive experience with Her-2 targeted treatment in breast cancer indicates that Her2 amplification predicts for response to such drugs.  However, the panel readily acknowledged that less is known about the efficacy of these agents in tumors of primary colon origin.  APC and TP53 mutations are extremely common in colon cancer and neither is currently predictive of response to available therapies.  The presence of APC and TP53 alterations does not appear to impact any clinical management decisions in this setting.
fields.title: Precision Oncology
fields.clinical_outcome:
The patient in this case had exhausted all of the commonly utilized therapeutics for the treatment of colon cancer and retained an acceptable performance status.  Genomic analysis performed in a certified laboratory indicated the presence of a Her-2 amplification.
 The patient received Trastuzumab every three weeks for a total of three treatments.  Follow-up evaluation identified a CEA of 29 (previously 15) and CT scan confirmed slight disease progression.  He then received Trastuzumab-emtansine every three weeks for two cycles.  Laboratory evaluation revealed a CEA of 13 and CT imaging confirmed clear evidence of disease response.  The patient went on to receive an additional three cycles of Trastuzumab-emtansine with CT imaging again confirming ongoing response to treatment (Fig 1D).
fields.history:
A 49-year-old gentleman presented to the emergency department complaining of right flank pain.  Initial labs revealed a hemoglobin of 7.1 g/dL, while imaging identified thickening of the sigmoid colon and multiple hepatic and pulmonary nodules.  Image-guided core needle biopsy of a liver nodule revealed metastatic adenocarcinoma consistent with metastatic colorectal cancer. Molecular analysis confirmed KRas-wildtype disease.

 Shortly after diagnosis, the patient began palliative chemotherapy with capecitabine/oxaliplatin.  Bevacizumab was not given due to evidence of rectal bleeding and a history of deep venous thrombosis. Three months after initiation of treatment, an interval CT scan confirmed stable disease.  However, follow-up imaging six months after treatment initiation identified progressive disease in the liver and lung as well as a new adrenal gland lesion.  Over the next several months the patient was treated with Capecitabine/Irinotecan and Irinotecan/Cetuximab ultimately progressing through each regimen with enlargement of hepatic metastases.  Given the patient’s age and excellent performance status, a repeat liver biopsy was performed and NextGen Sequencing diagnostic testing completed with the results listed below.
